.SH "NAME"
PPIx::Regexp::Token::Code \- Represent a chunk of Perl embedded in a regular expression.
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 3
\& use PPIx::Regexp::Dumper;
\& PPIx::Regexp::Dumper\->new(
\&     \*(Aqqr{(?{print "hello sailor\en"})}smx\*(Aq)\->print;
.Ve
.SH "INHERITANCE"
.IX Header "INHERITANCE"
\&\f(CW\*(C`PPIx::Regexp::Token::Code\*(C'\fR is a
PPIx::Regexp::Token.
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`PPIx::Regexp::Token::Code\*(C'\fR is the parent of
PPIx::Regexp::Token::Interpolation.
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This class represents a chunk of Perl code embedded in a regular
expression. Specifically, it results from parsing things like
.PP
.Vb 2
\& (?{ code })
\& (??{ code })
.Ve
.PP
or from the replacement side of an s///e. Technically, interpolations
are also code, but they parse differently and therefore end up in a
different token.
.PP
This token may not appear inside a regex set (i.e. \f(CW\*(C`(?[ ... ])\*(C'\fR. If
found, it will become a \f(CW\*(C`PPIx::Regexp::Token::Unknown\*(C'\fR.
